<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-577-720  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 577 720.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 24 1989 n1178 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The world here we come - in English. (learning foreign languages)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Haughton, Emma.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many English firms have yet to recognize the need to developforeign language skills in order to compete abroad.andP;  A recentstudy shows only 40 percent of UK executives can conduct abusiness conversation in a foreign language.andP;  IBM, Unisys, Hoskynsand HP all see English as the dominant language and limit trainingin foreign languages to a small number of people.andP;  IBM's onlylanguage course in England is for teaching English to foreigners.andO;But DEC's UK subsidiary, ICL and GEC Plessy Telecommunicationshave all stepped up courses in foreign languages, primarilyFrench, German and Japanese.andP;  Some computer firms are recognizingthe significance of learning a foreign language.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Foreign LanguagesEducationForeign CompetitionComputer IndustryInternational TradeEurope.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>